    "text": "et al., 2024; Yan et al., 2025). However, a unified convergence et al., 2024; Yan et al., 2025). However, a unified convergenceanalysis that compares all four topologies is still lacking. This theoretical gap impedes informed\ntopology selection in practical deployments, where system performance is highly sensitive to data\ndistribution and network conditions.\n(a) Star-Star HFL\n(b) Star-Ring HFL\n(c) Ring-Star HFL\n(d) Ring-Ring HFL\nFigure 1: Different topology configurations of HFL\nResearch Question. The central research problem is:\nHow should practitioners select the optimal HFL topology configuration when facing varying de-",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 1
  },
  {
    "text": "t the optimal HFL topology configuration when facing varying de-t the optimal HFL topology configuration when facing varying de-grees of intra-group and inter-group data heterogeneity, diverse client grouping characteristics, and\nconstrained network conditions?\nThis research problem is of practical importance for system convergence. For example, in systems\nwith high inter-group heterogeneity (such as clients clustered by geographic region with distinct data\ndistributions), selecting star topology at the top tier may amplify inter-group divergence through",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 2
  },
  {
    "text": "ology at the top tier may amplify inter-group divergence throughology at the top tier may amplify inter-group divergence throughabrupt parallel synchronization. Conversely, ring aggregation at the top tier enables gradual, se-\nquential alignment that may better accommodate distributional differences. This topology selection\nproblem is further complicated when considering diverse client grouping characteristics in HFL.\nAnalytical Challenges. Establishing a comprehensive convergence framework for HFL that encom-\npasses all four topology configurations presents three critical challenges:",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 3
  },
  {
    "text": "four topology configurations presents three critical challenges:four topology configurations presents three critical challenges:(1) Hierarchical Heterogeneity Interdependence. Unlike single-tier FL, HFL exhibits a cascading\nheterogeneity relationship where intra-group and inter-group data distributions interact in non-trivial\nways. This creates a feedback loop where local model divergence within groups directly exacerbates\nglobal model inconsistency. The convergence bounds must account for the multiplicative interaction\nbetween intra/inter-group divergence.",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 4
  },
  {
    "text": "multiplicative interaction\nbetween intra/inter-group divergence.multiplicative interaction\nbetween intra/inter-group divergence.(2) Cross-Tier Dynamic Coupling. The two-tier aggregation architecture creates a bidirectional de-\npendency where updates at one tier directly influence the error propagation at the other tier. The\neffective learning rate at one tier depends on accumulated errors from the other tier, invalidating\nsequential single-tier analysis approaches.\n(3) Compounded Topology-Specific Biases. Different topologies introduce distinct statistical prop-",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 5
  },
  {
    "text": "iases. Different topologies introduce distinct statistical prop-iases. Different topologies introduce distinct statistical prop-erties that compound across hierarchical layers in topology-dependent ways. Star and ring topolo-\ngies introduce fundamentally different statistical properties (unbiased high-variance updates versus\nbiased low-variance sequential updates) that compound across hierarchical layers. Such topology-\nspecific error propagation patterns require sophisticated cross-client error term analysis that explic-\nitly tracks how topology choices modulate bias-variance tradeoffs across hierarchical layers.",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 2,
    "chunk_id": 6
  },
