  {
    "text": "r convergence acceleration. Counterintuitively, HFL is primarilyr convergence acceleration. Counterintuitively, HFL is primarilyvaluable for enabling large-scale deployments where single-tier FL becomes impractical, rather than\ninherently accelerating convergence. Crucially, HFL with ring aggregation at the top tier (Ring-Star,\nRing-Ring) consistently outperforms star-based counterparts under data heterogeneity. This reveals\nthat carefully selected single-tier FL configurations may actually converge faster than two-tier HFL,\npositioning HFL as a solution for scalability constraints rather than a convergence accelerator.",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 3,
    "chunk_id": 4
  },
  {
    "text": "r scalability constraints rather than a convergence accelerator.r scalability constraints rather than a convergence accelerator.(2) Inter-group heterogeneity dominates convergence dynamics. We establish that inter-group data\ndivergence (Œ¥) exerts a more significant impact on convergence than intra-group heterogeneity (Œ∂)\nacross all four topologies. This finding fundamentally reshapes client clustering strategies, indicat-\ning that minimizing inter-group distributional differences should take precedence over optimizing\nintra-group homogeneity. Effective grouping, such as forming clusters with approximately IID inter-",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 3,
    "chunk_id": 5
  },
  {
    "text": "grouping, such as forming clusters with approximately IID inter-grouping, such as forming clusters with approximately IID inter-group distributions, would converge faster than fine-tuning intra-group training dynamics.\n(3) Optimal topology selection depends critically on group structure. Our analysis reveals optimal\ntopology selection depends critically on group structure. Ring-Star excels when numerous small\ngroups exist, as sequential inter-group updates benefit from increased parallelism at the lower tier\nand fine-grained global alignment. Star-Ring is preferable for few large, client-dense clusters, where",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 3,
    "chunk_id": 6
  },
  {
    "text": "r-Ring is preferable for few large, client-dense clusters, wherer-Ring is preferable for few large, client-dense clusters, whereintra-group ring aggregation enables deep local refinement before global synchronization.\nWe validate these theoretical insights through extensive experiments using ResNet-18/VGG-9 on\nCIFAR-10, ResNet-18 on CINIC-10, ResNet-10 on Fashion-MNIST, and MLP on SST-2 under four\ndistinct heterogeneity scenarios. The results consistently demonstrate accuracy gains from informed\ntopology selection, with ring-based top-tier configurations showing particular advantages in hetero-",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 3,
    "chunk_id": 7
  },
  {
    "text": "top-tier configurations showing particular advantages in hetero-top-tier configurations showing particular advantages in hetero-geneous environments. Beyond establishing the first convergence analysis for the previously unstud-\nied Ring-Ring topology, our framework overcomes critical limitations of prior work by: (i) adopting\nconsistent, general non-convex assumptions across all topologies, whereas previous studies relied on\n3",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
    "page": 3,
    "chunk_id": 8
  },
  {
    "text": "Published as a conference paper at ICLR 2026\nheterogeneous assumptions that prevented direct comparison; and (ii) deriving tighter convergence\nbounds of O(1/\n‚àö\nGPMKR) for Star-Ring and Ring-Star topologies, versus O(1/\n‚àö\nR) in prior\nliterature (Lee et al., 2020; Yan et al., 2025). These contributions provide system designers with\ntheoretically grounded principles for topology selection based on specific deployment constraints.\n2\nCONVERGENCE THEORY",
