  {
    "text": "+\nS\nrM‚ÜíG,g\n)\nRing-Star\nS\nr0‚Üí1\n+\nG\nX\ng=1\nœÑg +\nG\nX\ng=2\nS\nrg‚àí1‚Üíg\n+\n+\nS\nrM‚ÜíG,g\n)\nRing-Star\nS\nr0‚Üí1\n+\nG\nX\ng=1\nœÑg +\nG\nX\ng=2\nS\nrg‚àí1‚Üíg\n+S\nrG‚Üí0\nG\nX\ng=1\nmax\nm\n\u001a\nS\nrG‚Üím,g\n+ œÑg,m +\nS\nrm‚ÜíG,g\n\u001b\nRing-Ring\nS\nr0‚Üí1\n+\nG\nX\ng=1\nœÑg +\nG\nX\ng=2\nS\nrg‚àí1‚Üíg\n+\nS\nrG‚Üí0\nG\nX\ng=1\n(\nS\nrG‚Üí1,g\n+\nM\nX\nm=1\nœÑg,m +\nM\nX\nm=2\nS\nrm‚àí1‚Üím,g\n+\nS\nrM‚ÜíG,g\n)\nBandwidth Constraints and Practical Latency. Theoretically, the star topology offers advan-\ntages in parallel computation; however, in real-world scenarios, it often fails to achieve the\nidea O(1) level of parallelism.\nIn HFL, the total wall-clock time faces challenges similar to",
    "source": "iclr_2026.pdf",
